---
import Base from '../../layouts/Base.astro';
const base = import.meta.env.BASE_URL.replace(/\/+$/, '');
---

<Base title="Pre-empting a broker upgrade outage — Andrew Yang">
  <p><a href={`${base}/work/`}>← Case studies</a></p>
  <span class="tag">reliability</span>
  <h1>Pre-empting a broker upgrade outage: RabbitMQ 4.3 vs transient queues</h1>
  <p class="lede">
    The best incident write-up is the one that never needed to exist. Tracing a
    breaking change in a broker release to two language bindings of a shared
    library — before the upgrade shipped.
  </p>

  <h2>Context</h2>
  <p>
    Our services share a small eventing library for cache invalidation: every
    service instance declares its own short-lived fanout queue, receives
    invalidation events, and the queue disappears when the connection closes.
    The library exists in JVM, Node, and PHP bindings, used across the fleet.
  </p>

  <h2>Problem</h2>
  <p>
    A planned RabbitMQ 4.3 upgrade came with a deprecation that was easy to
    skim past: the broker now <strong>rejects transient queues that are not
    exclusive</strong>. Our JVM and Node listeners declared their per-instance
    queues as <code>durable=false, exclusive=false, auto-delete=true</code> —
    exactly the combination being removed. Had the upgrade gone ahead, every
    JVM and Node consumer of the library would have failed to boot its cache
    invalidation — quietly, at reconnect time, across the fleet.
  </p>

  <h2>Approach</h2>
  <ul class="clean">
    <li>
      <strong>Read the release notes like a diff against our topology.</strong>
      The audit found the risky declaration in two of the three language
      bindings; the PHP binding had already moved to quorum queues and was
      unaffected.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>Reproduce before believing:</strong> spun up RabbitMQ 4.3 in dev
      and confirmed the rejection with the library as-is.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>Fix with the semantics preserved:</strong> switched the
      declarations to <code>exclusive=true</code> — the officially recommended
      replacement, which keeps precisely the behaviour the library wanted all
      along: one private queue per instance, deleted when the connection dies.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>Roll out ahead of the upgrade:</strong> released the library and
      bumped every consuming project, so the broker upgrade landed on a fleet
      that was already compatible.
    </li>
  </ul>

  <h2>Impact</h2>
  <p>
    A cross-service outage that never happened. The upgrade shipped on
    schedule, with a verified fix instead of a 2 a.m. rollback.
  </p>

  <h2>What I'd tell my past self</h2>
  <p>
    Broker upgrades are schema migrations for your message topology — treat
    release notes as breaking-change lists, and treat queue declarations as
    code you own even when they live in a library someone else wrote. My
    <a href={`${base}/demo/`}>ai-radar demo</a> encodes this as a runbook rule:
    no broker minor bump without reading the queue-semantics changelog and
    rehearsing in a throwaway environment first.
  </p>
</Base>
